<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="product-lifecycle">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-operations</domain>
    <summary>Assess product lifecycle stage (Introduction, Growth, Maturity, Decline). Requires 6+ quarters of data. Apply stage-appropriate strategy, metrics, and investments.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>product-lifecycle</tag>
      <tag>lifecycle-stages</tag>
      <tag>product-portfolio</tag>
      <tag>strategy</tag>
      <tag>metrics</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Product Lifecycle Management</title>

    <summary>Framework for assessing which of four lifecycle stages a product is in (Introduction, Growth, Maturity, Decline) and applying stage-appropriate strategy, metrics, and investments. Assessment requires at least 6 quarters of revenue/growth/profitability/churn data. The key rule: strategy must match stage — growth tactics on a declining product and maturity investments in an early product both waste resources.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Products managed the same way regardless of maturity stage misallocate resources: growth spend on a declining product accelerates the burn, efficiency focus on an early-stage product starves learning. The lifecycle lens provides a vocabulary for portfolio decisions — which products to invest in, optimize, or sunset — and triggers transition planning a quarter before metrics shift so capability gaps (team mix, infra, KPIs) are filled in time.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Annual planning: assess each product/SKU stage, reallocate investment.</item>
        <item>Multi-product portfolio (3+ products): agent normalizes stage assessment when one PM can't intuit all.</item>
        <item>Pre-sunset decision: building a defensible "stage = decline" case before EOL announcement.</item>
        <item>Spinning out a product line: confirm growth-stage signals warrant independent team.</item>
        <item>Acquisition due diligence: independent stage assessment versus seller's claim.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Single-product solo founder still finding product-market fit — entire roadmap is Introduction; lifecycle adds no signal.</item>
        <item>Quarter-by-quarter operations — lifecycle changes on multi-quarter horizons; tactical decisions don't need this lens.</item>
        <item>Heavily-regulated products with mandated lifecycles (medical devices) — formal regulatory framework supersedes.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="stage-overview">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Require at least 6 quarters of data before making a stage assessment. One-quarter dip does not equal Decline.</statement>
        <rationale>Short data windows produce false stage calls. A temporary dip from seasonality or a one-off event looks identical to structural decline with fewer than 6 data points.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use category-specific baselines for growth thresholds, not the classic defaults (20%=growth, 10%=maturity). Consumer apps: 100%+; B2B vertical SaaS: 30%; mature enterprise: 10%.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs anchor on framework defaults. Injecting category baselines prevents misclassifying a healthy 15%-growth B2B product as "Maturity" when its peers grow at 12%.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="introduction-stage">
      <list>
        <item>Revenue: low or negative</item>
        <item>Growth: high uncertainty, frequent pivots</item>
        <item>Profitability: negative</item>
        <item>Competition: low</item>
      </list>
      <list>
        <item>Focus: product-market fit, learning, core feature refinement, user feedback</item>
        <item>Key metrics: activation rate, early retention (D7), NPS from early users</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="growth-stage">
      <list>
        <item>Revenue: rapidly increasing</item>
        <item>Growth: 20%+ YoY (category-adjusted)</item>
        <item>Profitability: improving, often breakeven</item>
        <item>Competition: increasing</item>
      </list>
      <list>
        <item>Focus: customer acquisition, feature expansion, team growth, infrastructure scaling</item>
        <item>Key metrics: growth rate, CAC, LTV, market share, MRR</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="maturity-stage">
      <list>
        <item>Revenue: stable or slowly growing</item>
        <item>Growth: below 10% YoY (category-adjusted)</item>
        <item>Profitability: peak margins</item>
        <item>Competition: intense</item>
      </list>
      <list>
        <item>Focus: efficiency, retention, incremental improvements, cost optimization</item>
        <item>Key metrics: profitability, churn, NPS, efficiency ratios</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="decline-stage">
      <list>
        <item>Revenue: decreasing YoY</item>
        <item>Growth: negative</item>
        <item>Competition: shifting to newer technology</item>
        <item>Customers: actively migrating away</item>
      </list>
      <list>
        <item>Focus: cash harvesting, managed decline, migration support, sunset planning</item>
        <item>Key metrics: cash flow, migration rate, support cost, timeline to sunset</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Sunset is a feature, not a failure: provide a clear migration path and grace period. Plan customer communications before announcing.</statement>
        <rationale>Silent EOL destroys trust and forces customers to scramble. Proactive migration support preserves the relationship and reputation.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="stage-appropriate-strategy">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Strategy must match stage. Growth tactics on a declining product and efficiency focus on an early-stage product both waste resources.</statement>
        <rationale>Mismatched strategy is the core failure lifecycle management solves. Growth spend on decline accelerates burn; efficiency focus on Introduction starves learning loops.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Introduction: MVP, iteration | awareness marketing | lean operations</item>
        <item>Growth: features + scale | acquisition marketing | build team and infra</item>
        <item>Maturity: optimize + extend | retention marketing | efficiency focus</item>
        <item>Decline: maintenance only | migration support | wind down costs</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="assessment-process">
      <list>
        <item>Step 1: Pull 8 quarters of: revenue, growth rate YoY, gross margin, net revenue retention, new logos, churn</item>
        <item>Step 2: Compare against category baselines (not framework defaults)</item>
        <item>Step 3: Assess stage with confidence band (High/Medium/Low) and alt hypothesis</item>
        <item>Step 4: Apply stage-appropriate strategy; identify misaligned current activities</item>
        <item>Step 5: Plan transition — what signals next stage, what capabilities are needed</item>
      </list>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every stage assessment must include an alt hypothesis: "what would I expect if this assessment is wrong?"</statement>
        <rationale>Single-hypothesis stage calls are overconfident. An alt hypothesis makes the assessment falsifiable and triggers re-evaluation when signals diverge.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="transition-planning">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Start transition planning one quarter before the expected stage change. Capability gaps (team mix, infra, KPIs) take a quarter to fill.</statement>
        <rationale>Stage transitions that catch teams unprepared result in wrong-stage activity continuing for months past the transition point, wasting resources.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent softening "Decline" to "plateau", "transition", or "consolidation".</description>
        <reason>Decline is emotionally loaded and agents soften it. Force the literal stage label in the prompt schema and validate the output field against an allowlist.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Declaring "back to Growth" from one quarter of re-acceleration after a PLG or AI feature drop.</description>
        <reason>Single-quarter re-acceleration could be a blip. Require 2+ sustained quarters before upgrading a stage assessment.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Conflating company stage with product stage in a multi-product company.</description>
        <reason>Individual products within a growing company can be in Decline. Specify product scope explicitly in every assessment prompt.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="human-in-loop-checkpoints">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Stage transition decisions (kill, sunset, double-down) are leadership decisions. Agent output is decision-support only; it never auto-publishes.</statement>
        <rationale>Stage transition triggers resource reallocation, team changes, and customer communications. These have organizational authority requirements agents do not satisfy.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations-and-gotchas">
      <p>Stage assessment from short data windows is unreliable — one-quarter dip does not equal Decline. Force at least 3 quarters of data. Adam Smith, Dean, and Vernon-style classic curve fit physical goods better than digital subscription products with re-acceleration loops (PLG, AI-feature refresh). "Maturity" detection biased toward growth-rate deceleration; misses cases where TAM expanded silently. LLMs anchor on framework's defaults (20% YoY = growth, etc.) — your category may have different baselines (consumer apps: 100%+; B2B vertical: 30%).</p>
      <p>Sunset and decline are often political: agents miss founder/team attachment that distorts data interpretation. LLMs use round-number thresholds (20%, 10%, 0%) rigidly; your category baselines differ. Inject baselines explicitly. "Decline" is emotionally loaded — agents soften it ("plateau", "transition", "consolidation"). Force literal stage label. Re-acceleration after AI or PLG feature drop reads as "back to growth" — could be one-quarter blip; require sustained 2+ quarters. Multi-product agents conflate company stage with product stage; specify scope in prompt. Confidence calibration is poor — "High confidence" on 6-quarter decline is real; "High confidence" on 2-quarter dip is fiction. Mandate data-window in confidence reasoning.</p>
      <p>Industry-normalization data is often paywalled (OpenView, ICONIQ); agent fabricates plausible benchmarks if not provided. Agents conflate market maturity with product maturity — your product can be in Introduction in a Mature market.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Use ≥6 quarters of data for stage calls; less is noise.</item>
        <item>Pair classic curve with modern growth-loop framing — growth loops and engagement curves replace some lifecycle thinking for digital products.</item>
        <item>Stage-appropriate KPIs: Introduction → activation/NPS; Growth → CAC/LTV/growth-rate; Maturity → margin/NRR/churn; Decline → cash flow / migration rate.</item>
        <item>Transition-planning starts a quarter before transition — capability gaps (team mix, infra) take time to fill.</item>
        <item>Sunset is a feature: clear migration path + grace period > silent EOL. Plan customer comms.</item>
        <item>Cross-product portfolio view: don't optimize products in isolation; killing a maturity-stage product to fund a growth bet is sometimes right.</item>
        <item>Stage call has alt-hypothesis discipline — agent must articulate "what would I expect if I'm wrong about this stage?".</item>
        <item>Re-evaluate after major external shift (regulatory, platform, AI disruption) — normal rhythm is annual.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-workflow">
      <p>Annual rhythm: (1) lifecycle-assessor agent ingests 8 quarters of metrics (revenue, growth, profitability, churn, NPS, market share if known) per product, computes stage with confidence band. (2) strategy-fitter agent maps current investments and activities to stage; flags mismatches (e.g. growth tactics on declining product). (3) transition-planner agent — when stage transition predicted, drafts capability changes needed (team, infra, metrics). (4) Quarterly: lighter delta-checker agent confirms or revises stage call from prior assessment. Critical: stage transition decisions are leadership; agent output is decision-support, not decision.</p>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/lifecycle-assessment.md" purpose="Metrics table (last year vs current), stage indicator matrix, assessed stage, actions to start/stop, transition planning."/>
      <template path="templates/stage-strategy-guide.md" purpose="Per-stage focus areas, KPI targets, investment priorities (High/Med/Low by function), risks, success criteria, transition triggers."/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://hbr.org/1965/11/exploit-the-product-life-cycle"/>
      <link href="https://www.amazon.com/Crossing-Chasm-Marketing-High-Tech-Products/dp/0887307175"/>
      <link href="https://www.reforge.com/"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
